<p><strong>
        <a href="/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/RyanJohnson.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-614"><img
                    class="size-full wp-image-614 alignleft" src="/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/RyanJohnson.jpg"
                    alt="RyanJohnson" width="249" height="249"
                    srcset="http://www.ict4dconference.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/RyanJohnson.jpg 249w, http://www.ict4dconference.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/RyanJohnson-150x150.jpg 150w"
                    sizes="(max-width: 249px) 100vw, 249px"/></a>Ryan Johnson, Global Client Services Director,
        Accenture Development Partnerships</strong></p>
<p>Ryan Johnson is the Global Client Services Director for Accenture Development Partnerships. Ryan has 17 years of
    experience in strategy development and program delivery with national and international corporations, governments,
    Non-Governmental Organizations and foundations.</p>
<p>
<div class="short_content_box">
    <div class="short_content"></p>
<p>Ryan has over 9 years of experience in the International Development sector and has worked on cross-sector
    partnerships, strategy engagements and program implementation in Africa, Asia, Europe and North America. Ryan has
    deep experience working with NGOs and foundations across their strategic, operational and technology challenges.</p>
<p>Recently, Ryan served as the first Director of Foundation and Corporate Engagement at Catholic Relief Services (CRS)
    while on a two-year secondment from Accenture. Ryan led the development and implementation of CRS&#8217;s
    agency-level corporate engagement strategy, design and mobilization of cross-sector partnerships, field capacity
    building and information management and communications. He oversaw a team responsible for institutional relationship
    management with the agency&#8217;s 21 largest foundation donors and also led the agency&#8217;s entrance into impact
    investing. Ryan&#8217;s work at CRS covered a spectrum of interaction that included philanthropy, cross-sector
    partnership, shared value creation and social impact investment in support of agriculture, health, emergency
    response, education and water-related programming. These efforts sought to advance CRS&#8217;s work to assist the
    poor and vulnerable overseas, and help to achieve program impact, innovation, scale and sustainability beyond what
    any one organization could achieve on its own.</p>
<p>Ryan has contributed to thought leadership such as the book Building a Better International NGO: Greater than the Sum
    of the Parts? and Accenture&#8217;s Convergence Economy: Rethinking International Development in a Converging World.
    Ryan led the design and planning for the first Vatican Impact Investing Conference, which CRS co-convened in Rome in
    June 2014 with the Pontifical Council for Justice and Peace and the University of Notre Dame. The Vatican Impact
    Investing Conference included leaders from the Catholic Church, USAID, the Social Impact Investment Taskforce
    established by the G8, Omidyar Network, Goldman Sachs and over 40 other organizations. The conference has launched
    an expanded discussion about the potential ways the Church might create or invest in impact investments to serve the
    poor around the world.</p>
